Exaggerate: The claim exaggerates the power of the Supreme Court by stating that it "can't overrule the other two" branches of government.
Understate: The claim understates the power of the Supreme Court by ignoring the fact that it can overrule laws passed by Congress and the president.
Lack enough support: The claim lacks enough support as it does not provide specific evidence or examples to back up the assertion that the Supreme Court cannot overrule the other two branches of government.
Problematic assumption: The claim makes the problematic assumption that the three branches of government are completely equal and cannot overrule each other.
Exist alternative explanation: There is an alternative explanation to the claim, as legal scholars and experts agree that the Supreme Court has the power of judicial review and can invalidate laws passed by Congress and the president.
